In `packages/blindfold/src/init.ts`, after a publish attempt (around the `... as Error).message` block) the code differentiates benign 'already published' failures from real errors:

```ts
const msg = (e as Error).message;
if (/version.*not higher|already.*registered/i.test(msg)) {
  warn(`Already published at this version — skipping. (${msg.slice(0, 100)})`);
} else {
  fail("Publish failed.", `Error: ${msg.slice(0, 300)}`);
  throw e;
}
```

Behavior:
- A regex test against `Error.message` (`/version.*not higher|already.*registered/i`) detects idempotent re-publish scenarios. These are downgraded to a `warn(...)` call (truncating the message to 100 chars) rather than aborting — useful when `npm publish` or a registry rejects a re-publish of the same version.
- Any other thrown error is surfaced via `fail("Publish failed.", ...)` with the first 300 chars of the message, then re-thrown so the caller aborts.

When publishing is skipped (`opts.skipPublish` flag) or no contract was built, an informational header is emitted:

```ts
