Within the `onData` listener of `packages/blindfold/src/prompt.ts`, the incoming chunk is first coerced to a UTF-8 string (`typeof chunk === "string" ? chunk : chunk.toString("utf8")`) and then iterated character by character with `for (const ch of s)`:

```ts
for (const ch of s) {
  if (ch === "\n" || ch === "\r") {
    cleanup();
    process.stderr.write("\n");
    resolve(buf);
    return;
  }
  if (ch === "\u0003") {
    // Ctrl+C
    cleanup();
    process.stderr.write("\n");
    reject(new Error("aborted by user"));
    return;
  }
  if (ch === "\u007f" || ch === "\b") {
    if (buf.length > 0) buf = buf.slice(0, -1);
    continue;
  }
  // Ignore other control chars
  if (ch >= " " || ch === "\t") buf += ch;
}
```

Behavior summary:
- **Submit (`\n` / `\r`)**: calls `cleanup()` (which presumably restores raw-mode terminal settings and detaches the listeners), writes a newline to stderr, and resolves the promise with the accumulated `buf` — i.e. the typed passphrase.
- **Abort (`\u0003`, Ctrl+C)**: cleans up, writes a newline, and rejects with `new Error("aborted by user")`. The rejected error propagates out so the caller can distinguish a user cancel from a real read.
- **Backspace (`\u007f` DEL or `\b`)**: pops the last character from `buf` via `buf.slice(0, -1)`, guarded by a `buf.length > 0` check so it cannot underflow. `continue` skips the subsequent append logic.
- **Other control characters**: silently dropped by the `if (ch >= " " || ch === "\t")` guard, preventing stray escape sequences (e.g. arrow keys producing ESC `[ A`) from being embedded in the secret.
- **Tab**: explicitly accepted (`ch === "\t"`) alongside printable characters and appended to `buf`.

This handler is what makes the one-file plaintext path usable interactively — the user types their passphrase on a TTY, the raw-mode stdin stream is decoded without echoing, and only the cleaned-up buffer reaches the caller. The strict filtering of control characters matters because the resulting `buf` is later used as the decryption passphrase for the TDX enclave blob, so any stray control byte would corrupt the key derivation.

