## Plaintext resolution in `packages/blindfold/src/register.ts`

After opening the enclave client with `openT3Client(env)`, the register command performs a **single, one-shot** plaintext read and immediately hands it off to the enclave. The three input modes are tried in this strict priority order:

1. **`opts.value`** — explicit programmatic API. Sets `source = "explicit"`.
2. **`opts.fromEnv`** — calls `pluckSecret(opts.fromEnv)` to read `process.env[name]`. Sets ``source = `env:${opts.fromEnv}```.
3. **Interactive** — falls back to `readSecretLine(\`  Value for "${opts.name}" (input is hidden): \`)` which prompts the terminal with echo disabled. If the returned `value` is falsy, it throws `"empty value"`.

```ts
let value: string;
if (opts.value !== undefined) {
  value = opts.value;
  source = "explicit";
} else if (opts.fromEnv) {
  value = pluckSecret(opts.fromEnv);
  source = `env:${opts.fromEnv}`;
} else {
  value = await readSecretLine(`  Value for "${opts.name}" (input is hidden): `);
  if (!value) throw new Error("empty value");
}
```

### Sentinel guard (prevents infinite in-enclave substitution)

Before sealing, the code rejects any value that contains the `SENTINEL` substring:

```ts
if (value.includes(SENTINEL)) {
  throw new Error(`Secret value contains the Blindfold sentinel string "${SENTINEL}" — this would cause infinite substitution. Use a different value.`);
}
```

This is critical because the T3 enclave wrapper uses the sentinel as the marker for **in-enclave substitution**: if the user's secret itself contained the sentinel, any later `unwrap`/forward operation would recurse forever replacing the sentinel with the same secret again.

### Sealing into the enclave

```ts
await t3.seedSecret(opts.name, value);
```

The plaintext only ever lives in the local `value` binding, is passed once into `seedSecret`, and is then dropped (per the inline comment: *"The local binding `value` exists here, is passed to seedSecret, then dropped."*). This is the **one-file plaintext path** property of Blindfold — the secret is never written to disk, never logged, and never held beyond the lifetime of the stack frame.

