From `packages/blindfold/src/wrap.ts`:

```ts
export interface WrapOpts {
  /** Defaults to http://127.0.0.1:<DEFAULT_PORT>/v1 */
  baseUrl?: string;
}

export interface OpenAIish {
  baseURL?: string;
  apiKey?: string;
  fetch?: typeof fetch;
}

export function wrap<T extends OpenAIish>(client: T, opts: WrapOpts = {}): T {
  const baseUrl = opts.baseUrl ?? `http://127.0.0.1:${DEFAULT_PORT}/v1`;
  client.baseURL = baseUrl;
  client.apiKey = SENTINEL;
  return client;
}
```

**Behavior**
- Mutates (and returns) the passed-in client — generic `T extends OpenAIish` so it works with the real `OpenAI` SDK or any compatible shim.
- Overwrites `baseURL` with `http://127.0.0.1:${DEFAULT_PORT}/v1` (using `DEFAULT_PORT` imported from `./constants.ts`) unless the caller supplies a custom `opts.baseUrl`.
- Overwrites `apiKey` with `SENTINEL` (also imported from `./constants.ts`). Per the file header: *"The 'apiKey' passed to OpenAI is meaningless; the SDK requires some string, so we use the sentinel."*
- Does **not** install a custom `fetch` on the client itself; the doc comment implies the SDK will subsequently route requests to the local Blindfold proxy because of the rewritten `baseURL`.

**Security property**
- The wrap layer never sees the real key. Substitution of the sentinel → real credential happens *inside* the T3 contract, downstream of the proxy. This preserves the "one-file plaintext path" model: a developer's source file never contains a real provider API key, even in an SDK-callable form.

**Usage shape (from the doc comment)**
```ts
import OpenAI from "openai";
import { wrap } from "blindfold";
const openai = wrap(new OpenAI({ apiKey: "__blindfold__" }));
```

**Note on constraints**
- `OpenAIish` is intentionally a loose structural type so the `blindfold` package avoids a hard dependency on the `openai` package — any object exposing `baseURL`/`apiKey`/`fetch` can be wrapped.

At the tail of the wrapping factory in `packages/blindfold/src/wrap.ts`, the produced client is finalized:

```ts
