`scripts/grant-and-call.ts` is a two-phase script.

**Phase 1 — egress grant.** Per the T3 dev team's `userClient.execute` recipe, it self-grants the tenant's own DID as an agent:

```ts
script_name: "tee:user/contracts",
function_name: "agent-auth-update",
input: { agents: [{ agentDid, scripts: [{ scriptName, versionReq, functions, allowedHosts }] }] }
```

Omitting this causes T3 to return `host/http.egress_denied`, which surfaces as an opaque 500 through the SDK path.

**Phase 2 — publish + call.** After the grant it registers `blindfold-proxy` v`CONTRACT_VERSION` (wasm loaded from `contract/target/wasm32-wasip2/release/blindfold_proxy.wasm` via `fs.readFileSync(WASM)`), tightens the `secrets` map ACL to `only: [contractId]` through `tenant.maps.update("secrets", { readers: { only: [contractId] } })`, and calls `forward()` so https://api.x.ai/v1/models is invoked with the sealed Grok key substituted **in-enclave** (one-file plaintext path; the key never crosses the WASM boundary in cleartext).

Setup wiring:

```ts
const env = loadBlindfoldEnv();
const sdk = (await import("@terminal3/t3n-sdk")) as any;
sdk.setEnvironment(env.t3Env);
const baseUrl = sdk.NODE_URLS[env.t3Env];
const addr = sdk.eth_get_address(env.t3nApiKey);
const t3n = new sdk.T3nClient({
  baseUrl,
  wasmComponent: await sdk.loadWasmComponent(),
  handlers: { EthSign: sdk.metamask_sign(addr, undefined, env.t3nApiKey) }
});
await t3n.handshake();
await t3n.authenticate(sdk.createEthAuthInput(addr));
const tenant = new sdk.TenantClient({ environment: env.t3Env, baseUrl, tenantDid: env.did, t3n });
```

Registration is wrapped in a try/catch that treats `/not higher|already|exists/i` as "already at v`CONTRACT_VERSION` — proceeding" rather than failing.

In the error branch of the `execute` diagnostic flow in `scripts/diagnose-execute.ts`, the caught value `e` is widened to `Error & { cause?: unknown; code?: string; data?: unknown }` and assigned to a local `err` variable. The script then emits a series of `console.log` lines to surface the failure context:

```ts
const err = e as Error & { cause?: unknown; code?: string; data?: unknown };
console.log("error class:", err.constructor.name);
console.log("error message:", err.message);
if (err.cause)  console.log("cause:",    JSON.stringify(err.cause).slice(0, 800));
if (err.data)   console.log("data:",     JSON.stringify(err.data).slice(0, 800));
if ((err as any).response) console.log("response:", JSON.stringify((err as any).response).slice(0, 800));
for (const k of Object.keys(err)) {
  if (!["message", "stack", "cause", "data", "response"].includes(k)) {
    console.log(`  ${k}:`, JSON.stringify((err as any)[k]).slice(0, 400));
  }
}
```

Behavior notes:
- Outputs the runtime class name (e.g. `ContractFunctionExecutionError`, `RpcRequestError`) and `err.message` verbatim.
- Conditionally prints `cause`, `data`, and `response` payloads, each JSON-stringified and sliced to 800 characters to avoid log blow-up.
- Walks every other enumerable key on the error (excluding the well-known `message`, `stack`, `cause`, `data`, `response`), printing it as `  key: <json up to 400 chars>`. This is the catch-all that surfaces SDK-specific extras such as `shortMessage`, `reason`, `code`, `transactionHash`, etc.
- After this block, the script transitions into step 3 — `console.log("\n=== T3 logs after execute ===")` followed by a second `try` calling `logs()` — so this introspection is the bridge between a failed execute and the post-mortem log fetch.

Relevance to Blindfold/TDX: these error fields are how a developer tells whether a failure came from the in-enclave TEE path itself, from plaintext RPC submission, or from JSON-RPC plumbing, which is critical when only one plaintext path is allowed for forwarding.

In `scripts/grant-and-call.ts`, the post-upgrade branch parses any thrown error via `(e as Error).message` and runs a regex test (`/not higher|already|exists/i`):

```ts
