In `scripts/run-tests.ts`, after spawning the test child process, the runner optionally arms a kill timer:

```ts
const t = opts.timeoutMs
  ? setTimeout(() => child.kill("SIGTERM"), opts.timeoutMs)
  : null;
child.on("close", (code) => {
  if (t) clearTimeout(t);
  resolve({
    code: code ?? -1,
    out: Buffer.concat(outChunks).toString("utf8"),
    err: Buffer.concat(errChunks).toString("utf8"),
  });
});
```

Behavior:
- When `opts.timeoutMs` is provided, a `setTimeout` is created; on fire it sends `SIGTERM` to the child.
- When the child emits `close`, the pending timeout (if any) is cleared via `clearTimeout(t)` to avoid killing an already-finished process.
- The promise resolves with `{ code, out, err }`, where `code` defaults to `-1` if null/undefined, and `out`/`err` are the UTF-8 strings of the concatenated stdout/stderr chunk buffers accumulated earlier.

This guarantees that a hung test cannot block the runner indefinitely and that the caller always receives a structured result with the captured output.

